# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: icmp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:icmp/icmpv6] ICMPv6 has a framework for extensions to implement new features.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Several extensions have been published, defining new ICMPv6 message types as well as new options for existing ICMPv6 message types.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] For example, Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP) is a node discovery protocol based on ICMPv6 which replaces and enhances functions of ARP.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Secure Neighbor Discovery (SEND) is an extension of NDP with extra security.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Multicast Listener Discovery (MLD) is used by IPv6 routers for discovering multicast listeners on a directly attached link, much like Internet Group Management Protocol (IGMP) is used in IPv4.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Multicast Router Discovery (MRD) allows the discovery of multicast routers.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] ICMPv6 messages may be classified as *error messages* and *information messages*.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] ICMPv6 messages are transported by IPv6 packets in which the IPv6 Next Header value for ICMPv6 is set to the value 58.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The ICMPv6 message consists of a header and the protocol payload.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The header contains only three fields: *Type* (8 bits), *Code* (8 bits), and *Checksum* (16 bits).
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Values in the range from 0 to 127 (high-order bit is 0) indicate an error message, while values in the range from 128 to 255 (high-order bit is 1) indicate an information message.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] field value depends on the message type and provides an additional level of message granularity.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Provides a minimal level of integrity verification for the ICMP message.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Control messages are identified by the value in the *type* field.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The *code* field gives additional context information for the message.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Some messages serve the same purpose as the correspondingly named ICMP message types.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Note that the table above is not comprehensive.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The current complete list of assigned ICMPv6 types can be found at this link: IANA: ICMPv6 Parameters.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] ICMPv6 provides a minimal level of message integrity verification by the inclusion of a 16-bit checksum in its header.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The checksum is calculated starting with a pseudo-header of IPv6 header fields according to the IPv6 standard, which consists of the source and destination addresses, the packet length and the next header field, the latter of which is set to the value 58.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Following this pseudo header, the checksum is continued with the ICMPv6 message.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The checksum computation is performed according to Internet protocol standards using 16-bit ones' complement summation, followed by a final ones' complement of the checksum itself and inserting it into the checksum field.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] Note that this differs from the way it is calculated for IPv4 in ICMP, but is similar to the calculation done in TCP.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The payload of an ICMPv6 message varies according to the type of message being sent.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] It begins at bit 32 immediately after the header described above.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] For some messages such as destination unreachable or time exceeded there is no defined message body.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] In the case of NDP messages the first four bytes are either reserved or used for flags/hoplimit.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] For a redirect the first bytes of the message body are reserved but not used.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] This is followed by a Target and destination address.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] When an ICMPv6 node receives a packet, it must undertake actions that depend on the type of message.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] The ICMPv6 protocol must limit the number of error messages sent to the same destination to avoid network overloading.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] For example, if a node continues to forward erroneous packets, ICMP will signal the error to the first packet and then do so periodically, with a fixed minimum period or with a fixed network maximum load.
[src:icmp/icmpv6] An ICMP error message must never be sent in response to another ICMP error message.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The **Internet Control Message Protocol** (**ICMP**) is a supporting protocol in the Internet protocol suite.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] It is used by network devices, including routers, to send error messages and operational information indicating success or failure when communicating with another IP address.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] For example, an error is indicated when a requested service is not available or that a host or router could not be reached.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP differs from transport protocols such as TCP and UDP in that it is not typically used to exchange data between systems, nor is it regularly employed by end-user network applications (with the exception of some diagnostic tools like ping and traceroute).
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] A separate Internet Control Message Protocol (called ICMPv6) is used with IPv6.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP is part of the Internet protocol suite as defined in RFC 792.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP messages are typically used for diagnostic or control purposes or generated in response to errors in IP operations (as specified in RFC 1122).
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP errors are directed to the source IP address of the originating packet.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] For example, every device (such as an intermediate router) forwarding an IP datagram first decrements the time to live (TTL) field in the IP header by one.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] If the resulting TTL is 0, the packet is discarded and an ICMP *time exceeded* message is sent to the datagram's source address.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Many commonly used network utilities are based on ICMP messages.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The traceroute command can be implemented by transmitting IP datagrams with specially set IP TTL header fields, and looking for ICMP time exceeded in transit and *destination unreachable* messages generated in response.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The related ping utility is implemented using the ICMP *echo request* and *echo reply* messages.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP uses the basic support of IP as if it were a higher-level protocol; however, ICMP is actually an integral part of IP.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Although ICMP messages are contained within standard IP packets, they are usually processed as a special case, distinguished from normal IP processing.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] In many cases, it is necessary to inspect the contents of the ICMP message and deliver the appropriate error message to the application responsible for transmitting the IP packet that prompted the ICMP message to be sent.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP is a network-layer protocol; this makes it a layer 3 protocol in the seven-layer OSI model.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] There is no port number associated with an ICMP packet, as these numbers are associated with protocols in the transport layer above, such as TCP and UDP.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The ICMP packet is encapsulated in an IPv4 packet.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The packet consists of header and data sections.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The ICMP header starts after the IPv4 header and is identified by its protocol number, *1*.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] All ICMP packets have an eight-byte header and variable-sized data section.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The first four bytes of the header have fixed format, while the last four bytes depend on the type and code of the ICMP packet.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] for error checking, calculated from the ICMP header and data with value 0 substituted for this field.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Four-byte field, contents vary based on the ICMP type and code.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP error messages contain a data section that includes a copy of the entire IPv4 header, plus at least the first eight bytes of data from the IPv4 packet that caused the error message.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The length of ICMP error messages should not exceed 576 bytes.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] This data is used by the host to match the message to the appropriate process.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] If a higher-level protocol uses port numbers, they are assumed to be in the first eight bytes of the original datagram's data.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The variable size of the ICMP packet data section has been exploited.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] In the "Ping of death", large or fragmented ICMP packets are used for denial-of-service attacks.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP data can also be used to create covert channels for communication.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] These channels are known as ICMP tunnels.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Some control messages have been deprecated since the protocol was first introduced.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Data is sent at a very high speed from a host or from several hosts at the same time to a particular router on a network.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Although a router has buffering capabilities, the buffering is limited to within a specified range.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The router cannot queue any more data than the capacity of the limited buffering space.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Thus, if the queue gets filled up, incoming data is discarded until the queue is no longer full.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] But as no acknowledgement mechanism is present in the network layer, the client does not know whether the data has reached the destination successfully.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Hence, some remedial measures should be taken by the network layer to avoid these kinds of situations.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] These measures are referred to as source quench.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] When a client receives this message, it automatically slows down the outgoing data rate or waits for a sufficient amount of time, which enables the router to empty the queue.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Thus, the source quench ICMP message acts as flow control in the network layer.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Since research suggested that "ICMP Source Quench [was] an ineffective (and unfair) antidote for congestion", routers' creation of source quench messages was deprecated in 1995 by RFC 1812.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Furthermore, forwarding of and any kind of reaction to (flow control actions) source quench messages was deprecated from 2012 by RFC 6633.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Time exceeded messages are used by the traceroute utility to identify gateways on the path between two hosts.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] All timestamps are in units of milliseconds since midnight UT.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] If the time is not available in milliseconds or cannot be provided with respect to midnight UT, then any time can be inserted in a timestamp, provided the high-order bit of the timestamp is also set to indicate this non-standard value.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The use of Timestamp and Timestamp Reply messages to synchronize the clocks of Internet nodes has largely been replaced by the UDP-based Network Time Protocol and the Precision Time Protocol.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Recipients should reply to this message with an *Address mask reply* message.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP Address Mask Request may be used as a part of reconnaissance attack to gather information on the target network, therefore ICMP Address Mask Reply is disabled by default on Cisco IOS.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] are not used, they are considered part of this field.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] field indicates the length of the original datagram data, in 32-bit words.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] This allows this ICMP message to be extended with extra information.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] If used, the original datagram data must be padded with zeroes to the nearest 32-bit boundary.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Contains the MTU of the next-hop network if a code 4 error occurs.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The IP header (20 bytes) and at most 548 bytes of the start of the original datagram (as not to exceed the minimum IPv4 reassembly buffer size).
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] If this message is extended, then this field must contain at least 128 bytes of original datagram data (padded with zeroes if necessary).
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] ICMP messages can be extended with extra information.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] This information is carried in one or more Extension Objects, which are preceded by an ICMP Extension Header.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] Checksum over this header and all extension objects.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] This field itself is included, so it is set to zero while performing the calculation.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] The length of the object in octets, including the header.
[src:icmp/internet-control-message-protocol] If nonempty, it contains a data structure, whose size is a multiple of 32 bits.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Ping measures the round-trip time for messages sent from the originating host to a destination computer that are echoed back to the source.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The name comes from active sonar terminology that sends a pulse of sound and listens for the echo to detect objects under water.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Ping operates by means of Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) packets.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] *Pinging* involves sending an **ICMP echo request** to the target host and waiting for an **ICMP echo reply**.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The program reports errors, packet loss, and a statistical summary of the results, typically including the minimum, maximum, the mean round-trip times, and standard deviation of the mean.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Command-line options and terminal output vary by implementation.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Options may include the size of the payload, count of tests, limits for the number of network hops (TTL) that probes traverse, interval between the requests and time to wait for a response.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Many systems provide a companion utility ping6, for testing on Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) networks, which uses ICMPv6.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The ping utility was written by Mike Muuss in December 1983 during his employment at the Ballistic Research Laboratory, now the US Army Research Laboratory.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] A remark by David Mills on using ICMP echo packets for IP network diagnosis and measurements prompted Muuss to create the utility to troubleshoot network problems.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The author named it after the sound that sonar makes since its methodology is analogous to sonar's echolocation.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The backronym *Packet Internet Groper* for ping has been used for over 30 years.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Muuss says that, from his point of view, *ping* was not intended as an acronym but he has acknowledged Mills's expansion of the name.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The first released version was public domain software; all subsequent versions have been licensed under the BSD license.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The FreeDOS version was developed by Erick Engelke and is licensed under the GPL.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Tim Crawford developed the ReactOS version.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Any host must process ICMP echo requests and issue echo replies in return.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The output lists each probe message and the results obtained.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Finally, it lists the statistics of the entire test.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] In this example, the shortest round-trip time was 9.674 ms, the average was 10.968 ms, and the maximum value was 11.726 ms.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The measurement had a standard deviation of 0.748 ms.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] In cases of no response from the target host, most implementations display either nothing or periodically print notifications about timing out.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] In case of error, the target host or an intermediate router sends back an ICMP error message, for example *host unreachable* or *TTL exceeded in transit*.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] In addition, these messages include the first eight bytes of the original message (in this case, the header of the ICMP echo request, including the quench value), so the ping utility can match responses to originating queries.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] An ICMP packet transported with IPv4 looks like this.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Can be used by the client to match the reply with the request that caused the reply.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Payload for the different kind of answers; can be an arbitrary length, left to implementation detail.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Most Linux systems use a unique *Identifier* for every ping process, and *Sequence number* is an increasing number within that process.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Windows uses a fixed *Identifier*, which varies between Windows versions, and a *Sequence number* that is only reset at boot time.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] An ICMP packet transported with IPv6 looks like this.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The payload may include a timestamp indicating the time of transmission and a sequence number, which are not found in this example.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] This allows ping to compute the round-trip time in a stateless manner without needing to record the time of transmission of each packet.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The payload may also include a *magic packet* for the Wake-on-LAN protocol, but the minimum payload, in that case, is longer than shown.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The *Echo Request* typically does not receive any reply if the host was sleeping in hibernation state, but the host still wakes up from sleep state if its interface is configured to accept wakeup requests.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] If the host is already active and configured to allow replies to incoming ICMP *Echo Request* packets, the returned reply should include the same payload.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] This may be used to detect that the remote host was effectively woken up by repeating a new request after some delay to allow the host to resume its network services.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] If the host was just sleeping in a low-power active state, a single request wakes up that host just enough to allow its *Echo Reply* service to reply instantly if that service was enabled.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] The host does not need to wake up all devices completely and may return to low-power mode after a short delay.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Such a configuration may be used to avoid a host entering hibernation state, with much longer wake-up delay, after some time passed in low power active mode.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] A packet including IP and ICMP headers must not be greater than the maximum transmission unit of the network, or risk being fragmented.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] To conduct a denial-of-service attack, an attacker may send ping requests as fast as possible, possibly overwhelming the victim with ICMP echo requests.
[src:icmp/ping-networking-utility] Ping requests to multiple addresses, ping sweeps, may be used to obtain a list of all hosts on a network.
[src:icmp/traceroute] In computing, **`traceroute`** and **`tracert`** are diagnostic command-line interface commands for displaying possible routes (paths) and transit delays of packets across an Internet Protocol (IP) network.
[src:icmp/traceroute] For Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6), the tool sometimes has the name **`traceroute6`** and **`tracert6`**.
[src:icmp/traceroute] A command is available in many modern operating systems, generally named `traceroute` in Unix-like systems such as FreeBSD, macOS, and Linux and named `tracert` in Windows and ReactOS.
[src:icmp/traceroute] On Linux, *tracepath* is a utility similar to traceroute, with the primary difference of not requiring superuser privileges.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Tracepath is part of the *iputils* group that contains the package *ping*.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The functionality was available graphically in macOS, but has been deprecated since the release of macOS Big Sur.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Windows NT-based operating systems also provide PathPing, which combines the functionality of ping with that of tracert.
[src:icmp/traceroute] On Windows, tracert sends ICMP Echo Request packets, rather than the UDP packets traceroute sends by default.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The time-to-live (TTL) value, also known as *hop limit*, is used in determining the intermediate routers being traversed towards the destination.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Traceroute sends packets with TTL values that gradually increase from packet to packet, starting with TTL value of one.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Routers decrement TTL values of packets by one when routing and discard packets whose TTL value has reached zero, returning the ICMP error message ICMP Time Exceeded.
[src:icmp/traceroute] For the first set of packets, the first router receives the packet, decrements the TTL value and drops the packet because it then has TTL value zero.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The router sends an ICMP Time Exceeded message back to the source.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The next set of packets are given a TTL value of two, so the first router forwards the packets, but the second router drops them and replies with ICMP Time Exceeded.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The timestamp values returned for each router along the path are the delay (latency) values, typically measured in milliseconds for each packet.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The sender expects a reply within a configured number of seconds.
[src:icmp/traceroute] If a packet is not acknowledged within the expected interval, an asterisk is displayed.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The Internet Protocol does not require packets to take the same route towards a particular destination, thus hosts listed might be hosts that other packets have traversed.
[src:icmp/traceroute] If the host at hop #N does not reply, the hop is skipped in the output.
[src:icmp/traceroute] If a network has a firewall and operates both Windows and Unix-like systems, more than one protocol must be enabled inbound through the firewall for traceroute to work and receive replies.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Some traceroute implementations use TCP packets, such as *tcptraceroute* and layer four traceroute (lft).
[src:icmp/traceroute] PathPing is a utility introduced with Windows NT that combines ping and traceroute functionality.
[src:icmp/traceroute] MTR is an enhanced version of ICMP traceroute available for Unix-like and Windows systems.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The various implementations of traceroute all rely on ICMP Time Exceeded (type 11) packets being sent to the source.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Cisco's implementation of traceroute also uses a sequence of UDP datagrams, each with incrementing TTL values, to an invalid port number at the remote host; by default, UDP port 33434 is used.
[src:icmp/traceroute] An extended version of this command (known as the *extended traceroute* command) can change the destination port number used by the UDP probe messages.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Most implementations include options to specify the number of queries to send per hop, time to wait for a response, the hop limit and port to use.
[src:icmp/traceroute] For Linux, *man traceroute* presents more details, including the displayed error flags.
[src:icmp/traceroute] In the example above, selected options are to wait for three seconds (instead of five), send out only one query to each hop (instead of three), limit the maximum number of hops to 16 before giving up (instead of 30), with *example.com* as the final host.
[src:icmp/traceroute] On line 8 and 9 (TTLs 8 and 9) it shows asterisks where the router did not respond within the timeout.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Traceroute can help identify incorrect routing table definitions or firewalls that may be blocking ICMP traffic, or high port UDP in Unix ping, to a site.
[src:icmp/traceroute] A correct traceroute response does not guarantee connectivity for applications as a firewall may permit ICMP packets but not permit packets of other protocols.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Traceroute is used by penetration testers to gather information about network infrastructure and IP address ranges around a given host.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Traceroute can be used to optimize data download.
[src:icmp/traceroute] If there are multiple mirrors available for the same resource, each mirror can be traced to find the fastest.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The traceroute manual page states that the original traceroute program was written by Van Jacobson in 1987 from a suggestion by Steve Deering, and that Guy Almes and Matt Mathis also had the idea concurrent with Deering.
[src:icmp/traceroute] The author of the ping program, Mike Muuss, states on his website that traceroute was written using kernel ICMP support that he had earlier coded to enable raw ICMP sockets when he first wrote the ping program.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Traceroute does not discover paths at the router level, but at the interface level.
[src:icmp/traceroute] Another limitation appears when routers do not respond to probes or when routers have a limit for ICMP responses.
[src:icmp/traceroute] In the presence of traffic load balancing, traceroute may indicate a path that does not actually exist; to minimize this problem there is a traceroute modification called Paris-traceroute, which maintains the flow identifier of the probes to avoid load balancing.
